{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112701/1018.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER FORECAST\nFair, not as cold .tonight, low 38. Partly\ncloudy, mild, chance of afternoon showers\nThursday, high 60. Colder at night. (Full\nreport on Page A-2.)\nMidnight 35 6 a.m.-..32 11 a.m 48\n2 a.m. 33 8 a.m 34 Noon 50\n4-ajn.--.32 10 ajn \u201443 1 p.m 53\n105th Year. No. 331. Phone ST. 3-5000 WASHINGTON, D. C., WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 27, 1957-40 PAGES Home Delivered: 8J& H3B\u00ab CENTS\nPresident Better, Talks to Aides\nFull Fuel Tax\nExempfionWon\nBy D.C. Transit\nP.U.C. Recommends\nThat $375,600 Fund\nBe Kept by Firm\nBy GRACE BASSETT\nD. C. Transit System. Inc.,\noday von from the Public\nUtilities Commission a full fuel\ntax exemption of $375,600 for\nthe year ending last August 31.\nP. U. C. Chairman George B.\n9. Hayes forwarded this rec\nommendation to the District\nCommissioners who must flnal\nly determine whether O. Roy\nChalk, transit president, must\npay the tax.\nThe P. U. C. asked that Mr.\nChalk be freed from the gas\ntax charges in accordance with\n.'his congressional franchise.\nCongress called for an ex\nemption to the extent that the\ncompany failed to make 6.5 per\ncent profits. The P. D. C.\nset the allowable 6.5 per cent\nprofit at $846,000. But D. C.\nTransit made only $589,488, the\nU. C. figures.\nNet Held to $213,000\nWithout the added income\ntax exemption given him, Mr.\nChalk would have made only\nslightly more than $213,000 net,\naccording to the P. U. C.\nThus, the difference between\nhis net income and the allow\nable 6.5 per cent was more than\nthe amount of the tax, entitling\nhim to the full exemption.\nThe P. U. C. finding was a\ncompromise between positions\ntaken by Mr. Chalk and his at\ntorney, Harvey Spear, and the 1\nP. U. C. chief accountant, Wil\nliam Falk and Counsel Lloyd\nHarrison.\n\u2018\u2018The commission sought to\ndetermine the course calculated\nto protect the interests of both\nthe community and the utility.\u201d\nMr. Hayes said.\nAt issue was the base on\nwhich the 6.5 per cent profit\nwas to be figured.\nAsked $lB Million Base\nMr. Chalk asked for a base\nof $25 million, representing\ngross operating revenue. Fail\ning this, he maintained the\nbase should be about $lB mil\nlion, representing roughly the\nprice he paid for the company\nplus his liabilities for streetcar\ntrack removal.\nThe P. U. C. staff urged the\ncommission to set the base at\n$B.l million, more closely\ngeared to the purchase price.\nThe PUC set the base at\nsl3 million, recognizing that\nthe staff had given \u2018\u2018no consid\neration\u201d to the cost of track\nSee TRANSIT, Page A-7\nDaughter Born to Wife\nOs Senator Kennedy\nNEW YORK. Nov. 27 UP).\u2014\nA baby girl was born to Senator\nand Mrs. John Kennedy at New\nYork Hospital at 8:15 a.m. to\nday. She is their first child.\nA hospital spokesman said\nboth mother and daughter, who\nweighed 7 pounds and 2 ounces,\nare doing well. Senator Ken\nnedy was on hand to greet his\nnew daughter.\nMrs. Kennedy, 27, the former\nJacqueline Bouvier, daughter of\na Manhattan financier, was\nmarried to the 40-year-old\nDemocratic Senator from Mas\nsaciweetts at Newport in 1953.\nPolice Private (by Act of Congress)\nLeaves $21,000 to Two Waitresses\nTwo waitresses who were\nkind to a steady customer at\nUnion Station\u2019s Gateway Res\ntaurant today found themselves\nsole heiresses to his surprising\n$21,120 fortune.\nMrs. Barbara Graas and Mrs.\nPauline Henson received with\nmixed emotions the news that\nWilliam C. (Little Willie)\nTruesdell. 63, a retired Wash\nington police private, left them\nthe money\u2014mostly In S2O bills\n\u2014tucked into a trunk along\nwith clothes and towels.\nMrs. Oraas, 42. was upset but\ntalkative.\n\u2018\u2018He told us one time he\nplanned to Include us in the\nwill, but we never thought any\nmore about it. We were as\ntounded this morning by the\nlarge amount of money he left.\u201d\nBureta Into Tear*\nMrs. Henson. 45, of 30 Ana\ncostla road S.E.. was too upset\nto talk. Questioned by a re\nporter, she would begin to an\nswer. then burst into tears.\nPolicemen who worked with\ni||r. Truesdell in the fifth pre\ncinct found the trunk after he\ndied late Monday in his rented\nroom at 312 First street S.E.\nAlthough the waitresses were\nsurprised at Mr. Truesdell s\naction, most of his Police De\npartment colleagues were not.\nAfter serving with him for 28\nyears and four months, they\n8m TRUESDELL. Page A-7\nWcyt Ibenina Sfe\nV V v v WITH SUNDAY MORNING EDITION\nFestive Thanksgiving\nDue for Weather Assist\nMany Take Four-Day Holiday;\nPrayers Planned for President\nThe spirit of Thanksgiving was in the air today as last\nminute preparations went forward for tomorrow\u2019s autumnal\nfestival.\nFor thousands In this area it meant the usual rush for\ntrains, planes and buses, with sights set on a holiday with\nrelatives or friends. Many Government workers were\nstretching it into a 4-day ex\ncursion by taking Friday as\nannual leave.\nThe weather looked en\ncouraging. The forecaster said\nThanksgiving Sarvicss in Area\nChurches listed. Page A-8\nit would be warmer tomorrow,\nprobably approaching 60 de\ngrees, and partly cloudy with\na chance of afternoon showers.\nTomorrow night promises to be\ncolder.\nThe joy engendered by the\ntraditional turkey, football and\ngood cheer will be tempered by\nPresident Eisenhower\u2019s illness.\nChurch-goers planned to re\nmember him in their prayers.\nBefore his illness, the Presi\ndent issued this formal holiday\nproclamation:\n\"Let the happiness which\nstems from family reunions On\nThanksgiving Day be tempered\nwith compassion and inspired\nby an active concern for those\nless fortunate in our own coun\ntry and other lands; and let\nus ask God\u2019s continuing help\nand guidance in our conduct,\nboth as individuals and as a\nNation.\u201d\nThe American Automobile\nArea Urged to Attract\nBusiness as Tax Move\nBy GEORGE BEVERIDGE\nWashington area jurisdictions l\nwere warned today that they\ncannot tax residents heavily\nenough to provide public serv\nices required by urban growth, i\nand that they must Intensify\nco-operative efforts to attract\nnew business and Industry to\nthe region.\nThis theme was stressed by\na parade of speakers at an all-;\nday conference at the Hotel!\nStatler under the auspices of!\nthe Washington Board of 1\nTrade\u2019s Economic Development\nCommittee and 10 other de\nvelopment agencies of the area.\nFormer District Engineer\nCommissioner Louis W. Pren\ntiss said the District is being\nforced to seek new industries\nas a result of the Federal Gov\nernment\u2019s failure to carry its\nfair share of the cost of run\nning the city.\n\"If the people of our Nation\nwant their Capital City to\nretain its Ivy League campus\nlike atmosphere in an area free\nof industrialization.\" he added,\n\u201cthey are going to have to pay\na bigger share than 10 per cent\nof the cost of operating the\nFederal City.\u201d\nOrderly Location\nGen. Prentiss, now executive\nvice president of the American\nRoad Builders Association, also\ncalled on the Federal Govern\nment to draw a long-range\nplan to provide for the orderly\nlocation of future Government\nbuildings in the area. He said\nhe was \"amazed recently\u201d to\nlearn that no agency is re\nsponsible for preparing such a\nplan despite the prospects for\njjfiW i tor\ny m* 1 I\nr wH\nmu w fcMgfcfc y\nI TiPMI\n\u25a0V Jw f w\naft*\ni f A v nj\nk x xk ODs\nA FORTUNE FOR SERVICE\u2014Mrs. Barbara Oraas\n(left) and Mrs. Pauline Henson, waitresses at the\nGateway Restaurant, Union Station, became heir\nesses today through the will of an old customer, a\nretired policeman.\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nAssociation estimates that some\n210,000 persons will leave the\nWashington area by car dur\ning the long holiday week end.\nMost of them will leave to\nnight. Not nearly as many\npersons will be coming in from\nother parts.\nBanks, schools and most\nbusinesses will be closed.\nTelevision offerings for the\nday will include the Macy\u2019s\nparade in New York and two\nfootball games. Texas vs. Texas\nA&M and the pro Detroit\nLIO9B vs. the Green Bay Pack\ners.\nHistorians can debate\nwhether this is the 337th or\n339th Thanksgiving Day. Tradi\ntionally the Pilgrims\u2019 feast In\nMassachusetts in 1621 has been\nconsidered the first Thanksgiv\ning. but there is reason to go\nback to 1619 in Virginia. On\nDecember 4, 1619, a group of\nsettlers arrived by ship from\nEngland at what is now\nBerkeley on the James River.\nTheir leaders proclaimed while\nstill at sea that \u201cthe day of\nour ship\u2019s arrival shall be\nyearly and perpetually kept as\na day of thanksgiving.\u2019\u2019\nfuture Federal growth. He\nadded:\n\u201cThe past and presently-em\nployed practice of permitting\nFederal agencies to scatter\nwilly-nilly throughout the com\nmunity needs to be abandoned.\nA procedure should b\u00ab set up\nunder which th4 United States\nGovernment will look to the fu\nture, prepare a master plan,\ndetermine where agencies are\nto be built and then require the\nagencies going into new con\nstruction to erect them in ac\ncordance with the plan.\u201d\nAt the same time, Gen. Pren-\nSee ECONOMIC, Page A-7\nBULLETINS\nSymington Shocked'\nBy Missiles Secrets\nSenator Symington, mem\nber of the Senate Prepared\nness Subcommittee, emerged\nfrom a secret briefing on the\nmissiles situation by CIA\nChief Allen Dalles today and\ntold reporters \u201cit is a sad\nand shocking story and the\nsooner the American people\nknow about it the better.\u201d\nHe did not elaborate. Sen\nator Flanders said that he\n\u201cwas a little bit disturbed\u201d\nby what he heard.\n(Earlier Story on Page A-7)\nAF Sets Jet Record\nNEW YORK UP). \u2014The Air\nForce today took back the\ncoast-to-eoast speed record\nfrom the Navy, flying from\nLea Angeles to New York in\nVoodo jets in 3 hours, 17\nminutes, 29.2 seconds.\nNATO Nations\nUrge Nixon to\nAttend Parley\nWant Event Held\nOn Schedule Despite\nPresident's Trouble\nPARIS, Nov. 27\nain, France, West Germany\nand Italy urged today that the\nscheduled NATO summit con\nference take place next month\ndespite President Eisenhower\u2019s\nillness, with Vice President\nNixon taking the Chief Execu\ntive\u2019s place.\nThese countries\u2014chief Euro\npean members of the North\nAtlantic Treaty Organization\nmade their views known in an\nswer to queries from the United\nStates delegation to NATO\nhere. Similar views were ex\npressed by the Netherlands and\nTurkey. Greece suggested a\npostponement.\nThe United States officially\noffered earlier today to send\nMr. Nixon, if this was agree\nable to the other members of\nthe alliance.\nInformed sources in London\nsaid the British view was that\nthe meeting still should be\nheld at the heads of govern\nment level and that there\nshould be no postponement.\nPoll Reported Under Way\nSpokesmen in some Western\nEuropean capitals had ex\npressed dismay at the prospect\nof meeting without Mr. Eisen\nhower in a session Intended to\nIncrease military and scientific\nco-operation within the Atlan\ntic Alliance to meet Soviet\nthreats.\nPaul-Henrl Spaak, of Bel\ngium. NATO secretary general,\nwas reported polling NATO\nmembers to see what they\nwanted to do about the meet\ning.\nFrench official souroes said\nthe French government sees no\nreason for postponing the sum\nmit session or for downgrading\nit to an ordinary ministerial\ncouncil meeting.\nNormally the foreign, defense\nand finance ministers of the 15\nnations meet hefe every Decem\nber for their annual review ses\nsion. This meeting, which would\nbe held concurrently with the\nsummit talks, fixes the NATO\nAlliance military preparedness\ngoaliL for the coming year.\nOfficials in the French For\neign Ministry studied the situ\nation closely this morning.\nTheir tentative decision was to\ngo ahead with the NATO ses\nsion even if Mr. Eisenhower\nmust be replaced by some other\nleading American personality.\nPella in Favor\nIn Rome, Italian Foreign\nMinister Giuseppe Pella said he\nbelieves the Paris NATO meet\ning should be held as sched\nuled despite President Eisen\nhower\u2019s Inability to attend it.\nMr. Pella, after meeting with\nItalian Premier Adone Zoli,\nsaid. \u201cWe hope that President\nEisenhower recovers soon. HU\nrecovery will enable us to count\nupon hU contribution to the\ncause of the free world.\u201d\nHowever, Mr. Pella added, \u201d1\nthink that the importance of\nquestions on the agenda of the\nParis NATO meeting is such\nthat it is not possible to post\npone it.\u201d\n'Silent Explosion'\nClaimed by Soviet\nLONDON, Nov. 27 (JP).\u2014Mos\ncow radio said today Soviet\nscientUts have devised a \u201csilent\nexplosion\u201d and have an atomic\nrailway locomotive on the draw-!\ning boards.\nThe broadcast said a Lenin\nirad scientist has found a meth\nod of splitting rocks of any\nsize by running a high-tension\nelectr. current through water.\n\u201cNo fragments are scattered\nfollowing the explosion. Nor\nis there any noise.\u201d the broad\ncast said, quoting from an ar\nticle in the publication Soviet\nRussia.\nAnother broadcast said So\nviet engineers Intend to build\n\u201ca super railway\u201d linking the\neast and west of the country.\nThe broadcast said the railroad\nwould have atomic locomotives\ncapable of pulling trains weigh\ning 50 to 60 times more than\npresent haulage maxlmums.\nPHONE SERVICE\nFOR THANKSGIVING\nTka Star'i holiday telephone ten\nwill ohierve the fallowing oper\nating hour! tomorrow:\nClassified Department: 9 a.m. to\n9 p.m. (Clatiifiad adi may ba\nplaced m person at the besmeu\ncounter in The Star lobby hem\na.m. to 9 p.m. I\nCirculation Department: 7 a.m.\nto 9:30 p.m.\nMere Switchboard: 7 a.m. fa\n12 p.m.\nAi usual, night sanrict linae will\nba placed ia operation sabeegaent\nto dating of mein switchboard.\nHolds Conference in Room\nWith Nixon and Adams\nm\nB JP\nJAN. 21, 1953\n\u2014v-* -r \u2014MWj\nJUNE 30, 1956\nf\nPRESIDENTIAL YEARS\u2014President Eisenhower\u2019s familiar smiles are\nshown (upper left) as he settled down to his desk at the White House\nto begin his first term; (upper right) at Fitzsimons Army Hospital, Den\nver, and (lower left) as he left Walter Reed Hospital after major surgery\nfor ileitis. At lower right the most recent photo was made at National\nAirport Monday while awaiting the arrival of Morocco\u2019s King\nMonamed V.\u2014AP Photos.\nNixon Confers\nWith President\nBy JOHN V. HORNER\nVice President Nixon went to\nthe White House again today\nand conferred with President\nEisenhower for 15 minutes.\nWhite House Press Secretary\nJames C. Hagerty announced\nthis afternoon that Mr. Nixon\nwas accompanied by Sherman\nAdams, assistant to the Pres\nident. for the visit with Mr\nElsenhower in a small studio\nacross the hall from the Pres\nident's bedroom on the second\nj floor of the Executive Mansion.\nThey found the President\npainting. Mr. Hagerty reported,\nbut he stopped to discuss the\nbudget now in preparation, the\nadministration\u2019s legislative pro\ngram and the forthcoming\nmeeting of the North Atlantic\nTreaty Organization in Paris.\nVice President Nixon spent\nmost of the working day at\nContinued on Page A-8, Col. I\nStocks Stage Recovery,\nGains Run to $7 a Share\nNEW YORK, Nov. 37 m.\u2014\nThe stock market advanced\nsharply today, recovering from\nIts severe break of yesterday on\nnews of President Eisenhower's\nillness.\nPrices were higher from the\nstart and by late In the morn\ning gains running to around\n17 a share were shown In lead\ning Issues. Oils were the\nstrongest group, but all sec\ntions pushed ahead.\nYesterday's break carried key\nstocks down as much as |7 a\nshare. It cut an estimated $4.5\nbillion from the quoted value\nof all stocks listed on the New\nYork exchange.\nIt was estimated that today's\ngains recovered about $3 bil\nlion of yesterday\u2019s loss.\nIn European markets, which\nwere closed at the time the\nmedical statement on the Pres\n\u25a0;\u25a0V'\n\nv\nifia* m jJI\nIllness Points Up Need\nFor 'Disability' Action\nBy ROBERT K. WALSH\nPresident Elsenhower\u2019s illness today gave Congress a new\nurgency to end delays and resolve varied and vexing discus\nsions that long have blocked solution of the problem of pos\nsible presidential disability.\nA mass of material, studies and specific plans\u2014some pro-\nposed by Mr. Elsenhower, him\nself, and by former Presidents\nTruman and Hoover\u2014awaits I\nthe return of Congress in Jan- 1\nuary. For almost two years\nmuch of it has waited in com\nmittee hearing transcripts, re\nsearch reports and dozens of\nlegislative bills.\nCongress in 1968 finally may,\nstart to take steps by clearing\ni the way for action on a specific\nistatute or constitutional\n{amendment resolution.\nThe prime question, unmen\ntioned and unanswered in the\nConstitution, is how and by\n{Whom there should be an off\nicial determination that a Presi\ndent is so incapacitated as to\nident's illness was Issued yes\nterday afternoon, prices gen\nerally declined today.\nI Quotations were marked\ni down at the start on the Lon\ndon stock Exchange, but then\ni recovered to near previous clos\ning levels. On West German\nstock exchanges prices dropped.\nAmong the leading gainers\nin New York this morning were\nCities Service. Phillips Petro\nleum. International Paper. Ken\nnecott Copper. Lukens Steel,\nZenith. Oeneral Dynamics. Bal\ni tlmore Sc Ohio, and du Pont.\nStocks have reacted dra\nmatically in recent years to\nPresident Eisenhower's health,\ni The biggest break came Sep\ntember 33, IBSS. the first trad\ning session after the President\ni had a heart attack. About\n113 billion was knocked off\nstock values that day.\nMetropolitan\nEdition\nNew York Markets, Page 1-9\nOCT. 25, 1955\nNOV. 25, 1957\nbe unable to perform his duties.\n'A companion question is how,\nand for how long, to provide\ni for the exercise of the powers\nof the presidency In such an\nemergency.\nThe Constitution Is clear\nenough In saylhg that \u201cIn case\nof the removal of the President\nfrom office, or of his death,\nresignation or Inability to dis\ncharge the powers and duties\nof the said office, the same\nshall devolve on the Vice Presi\ndent.\"\ni i\nNs Resignation Hint\n.1 There has been no hint by\nMr. Elsenhower, at least since\n1 the ileitis attack and operation\nIn June. 1955, that he contem\nplated resigning. On the con\ntrary, at a news conference last\nApril he was asked whether\nhis proposal to Congress for a\npresidential disability constitu\ntional amendment Indicated he\nwas thinking of resigning. He\ndescribed that as \u201cthe worst\nrot that I have heard since I\nI have been In this office.\u201d\nThe Constitution, while pre\ni else about the Vice President's!\nrole in event of resignation,\ni death or removal of a Presi\ndent, neither defines nor clari\ni fles \"Inability to discharge pow-i\ners and duties.\u201d Who decides--'\nand at what point Is It to b\nContinued on Page A-5. Col. 5\nCardinal Has Stroke\nVATICAN CITY, Nov. 37 (4>).|\nAdeodato Giovanni Cardinal\nPiazza. 73-year-old secretary of\n>ithe Vatican\u2019s Congregation of\nthe Consistory, was reported\nI today to be slightly Improved\nt after suffering a stroke yester\nt day that partially paralysed his\nleft side.\nProgress So Far\nIs Excellent,\nDoctors Say\nBy GARNETT D. HORNER\nPresident Eisenhower worked\nin his White House bedroom\nthis morning as his doctor re\nported that \u201chis progress to\ndate has been excellent.\u201d He\nis recovering from the mild\nstrokelike effects of a stoppage\nof Jalood in a small branch\nartery in his brain.\nThe President worked for\nhalf an hour on routine Gov-\nPartial Text of Prou Coniaraaca oa 1\nPresident's Illness. Page A- II\nVascalar Spasm Commonly Known as\nStroke. Page A-4\nCoarageovs, Nixon Says of Mrs. Eissa\nhawar. Pago A-4\nTaxts of Medical Sallctms. Pago A-4\nerament business, signing 12\ndocuments, and then conferred\nfor another 15 minutes with\nVice President Nixon and Pres\nidential Assistant Sherman\nAdams.\nSpeech Improving\nPress Secretary James C.\nHagerty said the President still\nhad some difficulty In pro\nnouncing long words this\nmorning, but that his speech\ndifficulty\u2014the only symptom\nof his illness\u2014is \"Improving\ngreatly.\u201d\nMr. Hagerty described the\nPresident as \u201camused\u201d rather\nthan worried about the slight\nspeech impairment.\nThe first medical report on\nthe President\u2019s condition today\ncame in a 1 pm. bulletin from\nMaj. Gen. Howard M. Snyder,\nhis personal physician. That\nstatement said:\n\"The President rested quietly\nthroughout the night and slept\nwell. He has spent the morning\npainting, talking with Mn El\nsenhower and other members of\nhis family and holding brief\nmeetings with the Vice Presi\ndent and the Assistant to the\nPresident (Sherman Adams)\nand with the staff secretary\n(Brig. Gen. Andrew J. Good\npaster). His progress to date\nhas been excellent.\u201d\nMr. Hagerty said the Presi\ndent haa \u201casked and received\npermission\u201d from his doctors\nto do some White House busi\nness.\nHe said Brig. Gen. Andrew\nJ. Goodpaster. White House\nstaff secretary, spent half an\nhour with the President. Dur\ning that time Mr. Eisenhower\nsigned 12 papers and initialed\nanother.\nMr. Hagerty said he also\ndiscussed other business with\nGen. Goodpaster.\nEats Normal Breakfast\nThe President awoke re\nfreshed after nearly 10 hours\nsleep, shaved himself, took his\nusual shower and ate a normal\nbreakfast before doing this\nwork. Mr. Haeerty said.\nThe only symptom of the\nPresident's illness was a \u201cslight\ndifficulty\u201d in saying long words\n\u2014and he was laughing at him\nself over that difficult, Mr.\nHagerty told newsmen.\nThe press secretary refused\nContinued on Page A-5, Col. I\nPella Coming to D. C.\nTo Talk With Dulles\nROME. Nov. 27 UP). ltalian\nForeign Minister Giuseppe Pella\nU going to Washington within\ntwo weeks to meet Secretary of\nBtate Dulles, an Italian Foreign\nMinistry spokesman said yester\nday.\nMr. Pella will exchange views\nwith Mr. Dulles on the forth\ncoming NATO meeting in Paris.\nHis trip follows visits of\nPrance's Christian Plneau and\nWest Oermany's Heinrich von\nBrentano. both foreign min\nj lsters.\nTWO SCHOOLS WIN\nTOP TEAM HONORS\nTHE STAR'S 1957 All Subarban\nMaryland scholastic football toam\nis dominated by two school!, It\nthasda-Chairy Chaw and Waltaf\nJohnson High. Tha makeup of tfca\nfirst and second towns, slang with\nthe playars' strong paints, art re\nported by Dick Slay and Georgs\nEragaw an fags A-16.\nGuide tor Readers\nAmnsam'ts $-6-7 Editorial A-12\nlusinass sad Featere Page $-16\nFinance I $-9 last, Foand A 3\nChurches A-$-9 Mask $-10\nClassified I-10 15 Obituary A-14\nComics S-16-19 Sports A-16-19\nCrossword $-11 TV-Radie 1-17\nEditorial Woman's\nArticles A-13 Section .1-4-5\nI Hove The Star Delivered to\n1 Yout Home Doily ond Sunday\nDial Sterling 3 5000","height":"28444","width":"18197"}}
